<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1901,1926]" pageId="8" pageNumber="129">FIGURE 5.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Vilhelmsen, 2020" authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" box="[280,543,1902,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocephalus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[280,543,1902,1926]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="129">Ophrynopus rufocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[548,604,1903,1926]" pageId="8" pageNumber="129" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, female holotype (NHML). A. Head and thorax, dorsal. B. Fore wing. C. Abdomen and hind leg, dorsal. Yellow arrow = groove between dorsalmost coronal teeth; blue arrow = occipital carina; green arrows = transverse pronotal carina; red arrow = vein cu-a; violet arrows = pegs on hind tibia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,1079]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis box="[199,305,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Pilosity indistinct. Tergum 1 areolate, with distinct postspiracular and subspiracular carina laterally, area below subspiracular carina glabrous. Terga 2-8 finely areolate to punctate, longitudinal carina on tergum 2 absent, smooth areas laterally on tergum 2 minute, hardly discernible (
<figureCitation box="[947,1036,224,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1901,1926]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,273,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[241,1346,273,1876]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ophrynopus rufocephalus n. sp., female holotype (NHML).A. Head and thorax, dorsal. B. Fore wing. C.Abdomen and hind leg, dorsal. Yellow arrow = groove between dorsalmost coronal teeth; blue arrow = occipital carina; green arrows = transverse pronotal carina; red arrow = vein cu-a; violet arrows = pegs on hind tibia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887934/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
). Tergum 9 finely areolate punctate anteriorly, coarsely areolate posteriorly, with distinct longitudinal carinae submedially; carinae short triangles with several spines aligned with them anteriorly. Abdominal sterna finely areolate punctate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,1079]" box="[199,389,333,359]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis box="[199,257,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Male</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,1079]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis box="[199,319,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species epithet, a noun, literally translates as ‘redhead’, which is highly appropriate (
<figureCitation box="[1314,1431,369,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1515,1540]" captionTargetBox="[224,1362,273,1490]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[224,1362,273,1491]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ophrynopus rufocephalus n. sp., female holotype (NHML). A. Habitus, lateral. B. Head, anterior. C. Antenna. Green arrow = transverse pronotal carina; red arrow = longitudinal carina on abdominal tergum 9; yellow arrow = groove between dorsalmost coronal teeth; white arrows = longitudinal lines on frons; blue arrow = notch in ventral transverse frontal carina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887932" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887932/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Figs 4A,B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,189,404,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1901,1926]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,273,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[241,1346,273,1876]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ophrynopus rufocephalus n. sp., female holotype (NHML).A. Head and thorax, dorsal. B. Fore wing. C.Abdomen and hind leg, dorsal. Yellow arrow = groove between dorsalmost coronal teeth; blue arrow = occipital carina; green arrows = transverse pronotal carina; red arrow = vein cu-a; violet arrows = pegs on hind tibia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887934/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">5A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,1079]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis box="[199,317,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Comments</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" box="[331,621,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocephalus">
<emphasis box="[331,621,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Ophrynopus rufocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a unique color pattern; a reddish brown head has not previously been observed in any 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="1996" box="[339,451,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Orussidae</taxonomicName>
described so far. The new species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[1055,1260,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seagi">
<emphasis box="[1055,1260,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Ophrynopus seagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a number of traits: the presence of a median notch on the ventral transverse frontal carina, the absence of a postocular carina, female antennomere 9 not swollen apically and without carina, the presence of a strongly developed transverse pronotal carina with a median incurvation, and the presence of a distinct medioventral groove on abdominal tergum 9. Apart from the color scheme, it can be separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[766,859,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seagi">
<emphasis box="[766,859,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. seagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the configuration of the dorsal ocellar teeth in a staggered, regular pattern (in low transverse rows in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[746,840,657,683]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seagi">
<emphasis box="[746,840,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. seagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the presence of a ventral longitudinal carina on the fore femur (absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[393,486,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seagi">
<emphasis box="[393,486,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. seagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), having the mesoscutellum less well defined laterally (with a glabrous strip laterally in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[180,273,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seagi">
<emphasis box="[180,273,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. seagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and having the smooth areas laterally on abdominal tergum 2 hardly developed (distinct in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[1316,1409,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seagi">
<emphasis box="[1316,1409,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. seagi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,1079]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">
The three faint longitudinal lines observed on the frons on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" box="[847,1026,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocephalus">
<emphasis box="[847,1026,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. rufocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1040,1126,765,791]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1515,1540]" captionTargetBox="[224,1362,273,1490]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[224,1362,273,1491]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ophrynopus rufocephalus n. sp., female holotype (NHML). A. Habitus, lateral. B. Head, anterior. C. Antenna. Green arrow = transverse pronotal carina; red arrow = longitudinal carina on abdominal tergum 9; yellow arrow = groove between dorsalmost coronal teeth; white arrows = longitudinal lines on frons; blue arrow = notch in ventral transverse frontal carina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887932" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887932/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
) probably indicates internal septa, which are observed in a number of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="1996" box="[634,746,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Orussidae</taxonomicName>
both extant and extinct (
<bibRefCitation author="Vilhelmsen, L. &amp; Zimmermann, D." box="[1033,1425,801,827]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" pagination="98412" refId="ref12560" refString="Vilhelmsen, L. &amp; Zimmermann, D. (2014) Baltorussus total makeover: Rejuvenation and sex change in an ancient parasitoid wasp lineage. PLoS ONE, 9 (6), e 98412. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0098412" type="journal article" year="2014">Vilhelmsen &amp; Zimmermann 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The septa serve as attachment areas for the highly developed extrinsic labral musculature in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Vilhelmsen 1996)" baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="1996" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Orussidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Vilhelmsen, L." pageId="9" pageNumber="130" pagination="143 - 170" refId="ref11912" refString="Vilhelmsen, L. (1996) The preoral cavity of lower Hymenoptera (Insecta): comparative morphology and phylogenetic significance. Zoologica Scripta, 25, 143 - 170. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1463 - 6409.1996. tb 00156. x" type="journal article" year="1996">Vilhelmsen 1996</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and are probably a ground plan feature of the family. The septa are probably easier to observe externally in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilhelmsen" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocephalus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. rufocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of its lighter head capsule coloration; in other more darkly colored specimens, it is not possible to see the trace of the septa through the head cuticle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,1079]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">
The 
<typeStatus box="[249,297,981,1007]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">type</typeStatus>
locality is also the place of the only previously published record of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Vilhelmsen" baseAuthorityYear="1996" box="[1049,1161,981,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Orussidae</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1228,1321,981,1007]" name="Ecuador" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Vilhelmsen, L. &amp; Smith, D. R." pageId="9" pageNumber="130" pagination="387 - 420" refId="ref12486" refString="Vilhelmsen, L. &amp; Smith, D. R. (2002) Revision of the ' ophrynopine' genera Argentophrynopus, n. gen., Guiglia Benson, Kulcania Benson, Ophrella Middlekauff, Ophrynon Middlekauff, Ophrynopus Konow, and Stirocorsia Konow (Hymenoptera: Orussidae). Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, 33, 387 - 420. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631202 X 00217" type="journal article" year="2002">Vilhelmsen &amp; Smith 2002</bibRefCitation>
); this is a female of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cameron" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[602,855,1017,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[602,855,1017,1043]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Ophrynopus nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, collected 
<date box="[981,1186,1016,1043]" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" value="1978-10-26">
October 26 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1108,1121,1016,1030]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">th</superScript>
1978
</date>
by M. Cooper. In the Appendix, additional records from 
<collectingCountry box="[545,638,1053,1079]" name="Ecuador" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[676,841,1053,1079]" class="Insecta" family="Orussidae" genus="Ophrynopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvostigma">
<emphasis box="[676,841,1053,1079]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="130">O. fulvostigma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are listed.
</paragraph>
